Wyclif answers (pp. 32—34) by enumerating various species of uni- versals. Some exist before their singulam, and are God's eternal ideas; some are mere passive potentialities3 others are founded upon the in- dividuals in which they exist; as, for instance, the idea of humanity. He then proceeds to deny that, when we apply the universal to its singulars, the supposition (application, or manner of using a word in a proposition) is other than personal. Now essentia] and personal suppositions are two very different things. When we say: “Humanity is animality together with rationality,³³ we have essential supposition; when we say that huma- nity comprises the man A, the man Β, &c. it is personal. In the first case the subject stands for all that is in the predicate; in the second, only for what is common to each of the singulars predicated. Thus, in the case aforesaid, ‘he’ would not stand for all the attributes of A and of B; one might be a king, the other a thief3 but lze would have nothing to do with the kingship or the dishonesty of its singulars.
